Macedonian referendum on renaming
Macedonia's people voted Sunday in a referendum on whether the country's name should be changed to "the Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has hampered the country's attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia, claiming that the name of its northern neighbour constitutes a claim on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments signed an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the name change would undermine the identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubts as to whether the minimum participation of 50 percent required for the referendum to be considered valid will be achieved.
The question on the ballot in the referendum is as follows: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth renaming if it makes Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia was split, able to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the outcome in order to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority of parliament.
According to the State Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
But participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last 2016 parliamentary election when 66% of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonia’s Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dusko vote in the Macedonian referendum on the country’s name change, which would pave the way for NATO and European Union membership, in Strumica, Macedonia 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, arranged a small stage and set up chairs in front of the tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with the head in the air, not sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don’t welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, like China and Russia, and become part of a Euro-Asian integration.”
According to Prime Minister Zaev, a NATO membership would lead to much-needed investments in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
“I think the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80 percent of our residents are for the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
He said a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a survey published Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Policy Survey, between 30 and 43 percent of voters thought to vote in the referendum, which falls below the minimum participation required.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of participants thought to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them voted yes.
In order for the referendum to be counted, 50 percent of registered voters plus one vote must be counted.
