While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a nuclear approach divided into stages that would lead to North Korea’s reward when it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a one-sided nuclear-weapon solution as such.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards "development of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused negotiations to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on “decommissioning first” and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even opposes the “declaration of ending the war,” Ri says.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream for those people who lack knowledge about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader stressed at the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a dead end."
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the US mainland with missiles was inevitable after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, gave praise to Kim for his courage to take action on disarmament, but it said that much work remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
