Rarity students take courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has got all doctoral students to improve their sleep habits in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-filled “highs.”
One academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often careless when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why can’t I know this until now, during my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organized for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course covers a range of interactive tasks.
In part of the course there is a picture of a student room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to find out about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants will learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students directly.
But we think they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride culture in that "dignity" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in a state of hunger and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has read one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all PhD students to complete a similar study programme before they begin their studies at the high-performing institution.
