Algae flowering: stops decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in algae bloom concentrations for parts of the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven flowers are reported in the areas surrounding the municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which may indicate a decrease in levels.
The algae bloom stretches over 20 miles of the coast, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee.
Spots can be seen about one and a half miles out into the sea outside the large municipality of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algae blooming has also been observed in the large municipality of Pasco.
Mean concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas have been reported during the past week. Off the coast of Hillsborough low to high concentrations, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manatee, background concentrations to high concentrations in or off the coast of Sarasota, background concentrations in skeletons, and concentrations in skeletons to medium.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come from the major municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in northwest Florida last week.
